## Description {#details}

This file provides utility analysis objects describing memory locations.

These are used both by the Alias Analysis infrastructure and more specialized memory analysis layers.

<Link id="l00041" /><CodeLine lineNumber="41"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// Represents the size of a MemoryLocation. Logically, it&#39;s an</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00042" /><CodeLine lineNumber="42"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// std::optional&lt;uint63&#95;t&gt; that also carries a bit to represent whether the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00043" /><CodeLine lineNumber="43"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// integer it contains, N, is &#39;precise&#39;. Precise, in this context, means that we</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00044" /><CodeLine lineNumber="44"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// know that the area of storage referenced by the given MemoryLocation must be</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00045" /><CodeLine lineNumber="45"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// precisely N bytes. An imprecise value is formed as the union of two or more</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00046" /><CodeLine lineNumber="46"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// precise values, and can conservatively represent all of the values unioned</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00047" /><CodeLine lineNumber="47"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// into it. Importantly, imprecise values are an &#42;upper-bound&#42; on the size of a</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00048" /><CodeLine lineNumber="48"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// MemoryLocation.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00049" /><CodeLine lineNumber="49"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00050" /><CodeLine lineNumber="50"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// Concretely, a precise MemoryLocation is (%p, 4) in</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00051" /><CodeLine lineNumber="51"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// store i32 0, i32&#42; %p</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00052" /><CodeLine lineNumber="52"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00053" /><CodeLine lineNumber="53"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// Since we know that %p must be at least 4 bytes large at this point.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00054" /><CodeLine lineNumber="54"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// Otherwise, we have UB. An example of an imprecise MemoryLocation is (%p, 4)</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00055" /><CodeLine lineNumber="55"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// at the memcpy in</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00056" /><CodeLine lineNumber="56"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00057" /><CodeLine lineNumber="57"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   %n = select i1 %foo, i64 1, i64 4</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00058" /><CodeLine lineNumber="58"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   call void @llvm.memcpy.p0i8.p0i8.i64(i8&#42; %p, i8&#42; %baz, i64 %n, i32 1,</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00059" /><CodeLine lineNumber="59"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//                                        i1 false)</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00060" /><CodeLine lineNumber="60"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00061" /><CodeLine lineNumber="61"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// ...Since we&#39;ll copy &#42;up to&#42; 4 bytes into %p, but we can&#39;t guarantee that</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00062" /><CodeLine lineNumber="62"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// we&#39;ll ever actually do so.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00063" /><CodeLine lineNumber="63"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00064" /><CodeLine lineNumber="64"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// If asked to represent a pathologically large value, this will degrade to</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00065" /><CodeLine lineNumber="65"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// std::nullopt.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00066" /><CodeLine lineNumber="66"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// Store Scalable information in bit 62 of Value. Scalable information is</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00067" /><CodeLine lineNumber="67"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// required to do Alias Analysis on Scalable quantities</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00068" /><CodeLine lineNumber="68" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/llvm/locationsize"><span class="doxyHighlightKeyword">class </span><span class="doxyHighlight">LocationSize &#123;</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00218" /><CodeLine lineNumber="218"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// Representation for a specific memory location.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00219" /><CodeLine lineNumber="219"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00220" /><CodeLine lineNumber="220"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// This abstraction can be used to represent a specific location in memory.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00221" /><CodeLine lineNumber="221"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// The goal of the location is to represent enough information to describe</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00222" /><CodeLine lineNumber="222"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// abstract aliasing, modification, and reference behaviors of whatever</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00223" /><CodeLine lineNumber="223"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// value(s) are stored in memory at the particular location.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00224" /><CodeLine lineNumber="224"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00225" /><CodeLine lineNumber="225"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// The primary user of this interface is LLVM&#39;s Alias Analysis, but other</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00226" /><CodeLine lineNumber="226"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// memory analyses such as MemoryDependence can use it as well.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00227" /><CodeLine lineNumber="227" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/llvm/memorylocation"><span class="doxyHighlightKeyword">class </span><span class="doxyHighlight"><a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/memorylocation/#aa17d3cf450fd3c75aaf0233578d73341">MemoryLocation</a> &#123;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00228" /><CodeLine lineNumber="228"><span class="doxyHighlightKeyword">public</span><span class="doxyHighlight">:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00229" /><CodeLine lineNumber="229"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// UnknownSize - This is a special value which can be used with the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00230" /><CodeLine lineNumber="230"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// size arguments in alias queries to indicate that the caller does not</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00231" /><CodeLine lineNumber="231"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// know the sizes of the potential memory references.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00232" /><CodeLine lineNumber="232" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/llvm/memorylocation/#a031e3abd6e1a18f9462f7cee212ba004a33f7f25590a5334874e8a114e6f5e55f"><span class="doxyHighlight">  enum : uint64&#95;t &#123; <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/memorylocation/#a031e3abd6e1a18f9462f7cee212ba004a33f7f25590a5334874e8a114e6f5e55f">UnknownSize</a> = ~UINT64&#95;C(0) &#125;;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00233" /><CodeLine lineNumber="233"></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00234" /><CodeLine lineNumber="234"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// The address of the start of the location.</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00236" /><CodeLine lineNumber="236"></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00237" /><CodeLine lineNumber="237"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// The maximum size of the location, in address-units, or</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00238" /><CodeLine lineNumber="238"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// UnknownSize if the size is not known.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00239" /><CodeLine lineNumber="239"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00240" /><CodeLine lineNumber="240"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// Note that an unknown size does not mean the pointer aliases the entire</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00241" /><CodeLine lineNumber="241"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// virtual address space, because there are restrictions on stepping out of</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00242" /><CodeLine lineNumber="242"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// one object and into another. See</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00243" /><CodeLine lineNumber="243"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// http://llvm.org/docs/LangRef.html#pointeraliasing</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00244" /><CodeLine lineNumber="244" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/llvm/memorylocation/#a39f7ff959874bf38f3e14aa0b2622da0"><span class="doxyHighlight">  <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/locationsize">LocationSize</a> <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/memorylocation/#a39f7ff959874bf38f3e14aa0b2622da0">Size</a>;</span></CodeLine>
